            </fr:date>
            <fr:anchor>11286</fr:anchor>
            <fr:addr type="user">jms-00K7</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00K7.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Partial function">Partial function</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A <fr:link href="jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R\colon  A\mathbin {\nrightarrow } B]]></fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em><fr:strong>functional</fr:strong></fr:em> when it relates an element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:em>at most</fr:em> one element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>:</fr:p>
            <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
 \forall  a\in  A\mathpunct {.}
 \forall  b_1,b_2\in  B\mathpunct {.}
 a\mathrel {R}b_1\land  a\mathrel {R}b_2
 \implies 
 b_1 = b_2
]]></fr:tex>
            <fr:p>We refer to a functional <fr:link href="jms-00I7.xml" title="Relation" addr="jms-00I7" type="local">relation</fr:link> as a <fr:em><fr:strong>partial function</fr:strong></fr:em>; we often use letters like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f,g]]></fr:tex> to refer to partial functions rather than <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R,S]]></fr:tex>. When we write <html:span style="white-space: nowrap" xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">“<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  A\to  B]]></fr:tex>”</html:span>, we mean that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is a partial function from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
